  "prompt": "What will be the effect of note ban in real estate?",
  "response": "The demonetization or note ban in India, implemented in November 2016, had several significant effects on the real estate sector:\n\n1. Short-term market slowdown\n- Reduced liquidity\n- Decreased property transactions\n- Temporary market uncertainty\n\n2. Reduced cash transactions\n- Decreased black money in real estate\n- Increased transparency in property dealings\n- Pushed towards digital and formal transactions\n\n3. Price correction\n- Property prices stabilized\n- Reduction in speculative investments\n- More realistic property valuations\n\n4. Increased formal banking channels\n- Greater use of bank loans\n- More structured property purchases\n- Improved documentation\n\n5. Long-term sector transformation\n- Enhanced regulatory compliance\n- Improved investor confidence\n- Gradual shift towards organized real estate\n\n6. Inventory clearance\n- Unsold inventory became more attractive\n- Developers offered better deals\n- Improved market sentiment\n\n7. RERA and GST implementation\n- Complemented demonetization's transparency goals\n- Increased accountability in real estate sector\n- Improved investor protection\n\n8. Temporary investment slowdown\n- Reduced investor interest\n- Cautious approach to property investments\n- Longer sales cycles\n\nThese effects collectively transformed the real estate sector, promoting more formal and transparent transactions.",
